# Bug Report: `failOn*="false"` XML attributes are silently ignored when `failOnAllIssues="true"` is set

## Summary

I ran into this while setting up `failOnAllIssues="true"` in my `phpunit.xml` and trying to carve out an exception for self-deprecations with `failOnSelfDeprecation="false"`. It didn't work — the build kept failing on self-deprecations anyway. After digging into the source, I found that none of the granular `failOn*="false"` overrides can turn a specific issue type back off once `failOnAllIssues="true"` is set. The only way to override it is through the `--do-not-fail-on-*` family of CLI flags, and those have no XML equivalent at all. This isn't just a `failOnSelfDeprecation` problem either — I checked, and it affects all 13 `failOn*` settings that `failOnAllIssues` touches.

- **Type:** Logic bug (configuration precedence)
- **Affected version:** PHPUnit 13.3-g92a2b54 (current `main`, still present as of this report)
- **Affected file:** `src/TextUI/ShellExitCodeCalculator.php`
- **Tested on:** PHP 8.4.22

## How to reproduce it

**`src/FirstParty.php`** — something that triggers a self-deprecation:
```php
<?php declare(strict_types=1);
namespace PoC;

final class FirstParty
{
    public function triggerDeprecation(): void
    {
        trigger_error('self deprecation in first-party code', E_USER_DEPRECATED);
    }
}
```

**`tests/SelfDeprecationTest.php`:**
```php
<?php declare(strict_types=1);
namespace PoC;

use PHPUnit\Framework\TestCase;
require_once __DIR__ . '/../src/FirstParty.php';

final class SelfDeprecationTest extends TestCase
{
    public function testSelfDeprecation(): void
    {
        (new FirstParty)->triggerDeprecation();
        $this->assertTrue(true);
    }
}
```

**`phpunit.xml`:**
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<phpunit cacheResult="false"
         failOnAllIssues="true"
         failOnSelfDeprecation="false">
    <testsuites>
        <testsuite name="default">
            <directory>tests</directory>
        </testsuite>
    </testsuites>
    <source>
        <include>
            <directory>src</directory>
        </include>
    </source>
</phpunit>
```

Running this:
```console
$ php phpunit --configuration phpunit.xml
PHPUnit 13.3-g92a2b54 by Sebastian Bergmann and contributors.
Runtime:       PHP 8.4.22
Configuration: /tmp/bug-poc/phpunit.xml

D                                                                   1 / 1 (100%)

Time: 00:00.001, Memory: 20.00 MB

1 test triggered 1 deprecation:

1) /tmp/bug-poc/src/FirstParty.php:7
self deprecation in first-party code

Triggered by:

* PoC\SelfDeprecationTest::testSelfDeprecation
  /tmp/bug-poc/tests/SelfDeprecationTest.php:8

OK, but there were issues!
Tests: 1, Assertions: 1, Deprecations: 1.

$ echo $?
1
```

I expected exit code `0` since I explicitly set `failOnSelfDeprecation="false"`. Instead I got `1`. The `false` value is just silently thrown away.

To confirm it's specifically an XML problem, I ran the exact same config with the CLI flag added:
```console
$ php phpunit --configuration phpunit.xml --do-not-fail-on-self-deprecation
[... identical test output and deprecation report ...]
OK, but there were issues!
Tests: 1, Assertions: 1, Deprecations: 1.

$ echo $?
0
```

Same test, same deprecation, same reported output — the only thing that changed is where the override came from. That pretty much isolates this to the config-merging/exit-code logic, not the test run itself.

## Why this happens

I traced it down to `src/TextUI/ShellExitCodeCalculator.php`, lines 39–70:

```php
if ($configuration->failOnAllIssues()) {
    $failOnDeprecation        = true;
    // ... (10 other flags set true) ...
}

if ($configuration->failOnDeprecation()) {
    $failOnDeprecation = true;
}

if ($configuration->doNotFailOnDeprecation()) {
    $failOnDeprecation = false;
}

$failOnSelfDeprecation     = $failOnDeprecation;   // inherits true from failOnAllIssues
$failOnDirectDeprecation   = $failOnDeprecation;
$failOnIndirectDeprecation = $failOnDeprecation;

if ($configuration->failOnSelfDeprecation()) {      // false → this is skipped, no-op
    $failOnSelfDeprecation = true;
}

if ($configuration->doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation()) { // the only path back to false
    $failOnSelfDeprecation = false;
}
```

`failOnSelfDeprecation()` is a plain boolean, so it can only ever push the flag from `false` to `true`. There's no way to distinguish "the user didn't mention this setting" from "the user explicitly set it to false" — both look the same. The only thing that can force the flag back to `false` is `doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation()`.

And that's where it breaks for XML users. In `src/TextUI/Configuration/Merger.php`, lines 234–238:

```php
$doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation = false;

if ($cliConfiguration->hasDoNotFailOnSelfDeprecation()) {
    $doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation = $cliConfiguration->doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation();
}
```

There's no `elseif ($xmlConfiguration->...)` branch here. I checked the whole file, and this exact pattern — CLI-only, no XML fallback — repeats identically for all 13 `doNotFailOn*` variables: `doNotFailOnDeprecation`, `doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation`, `doNotFailOnDirectDeprecation`, `doNotFailOnIndirectDeprecation`, `doNotFailOnPhpunitDeprecation`, `doNotFailOnPhpunitNotice`, `doNotFailOnPhpunitWarning`, `doNotFailOnEmptyTestSuite`, `doNotFailOnIncomplete`, `doNotFailOnNotice`, `doNotFailOnRisky`, `doNotFailOnSkipped`, `doNotFailOnWarning`. None of them can be set from `phpunit.xml`.

The `--do-not-fail-on-*` flags clearly exist to let people carve out exceptions from a blanket `failOnAllIssues` — that override mechanism just never got wired up for the XML side.

A couple of things made me fairly confident this isn't intentional:

- There's no test file anywhere for `ShellExitCodeCalculator` at all (`find . -iname "*ShellExitCode*"` only turns up the source file). This precedence interaction has never been tested.
- The schema doesn't document any override relationship either — `phpunit.xsd` just declares both as independent booleans with no annotation:
  ```xml
  <xs:attribute name="failOnAllIssues" type="xs:boolean" default="false"/>
  <xs:attribute name="failOnSelfDeprecation" type="xs:boolean" default="false"/>
  ```
  If this were by design, I'd expect it to be documented somewhere near here.
- The existence of the `--do-not-fail-on-*` flags at all tells me granular override of `failOnAllIssues` was a deliberate goal — it just never got finished for the XML side.

## Why this matters in practice

This is a CI/CD correctness bug, not a security issue — I know PHPUnit's `SECURITY.md` puts CI/CD pipeline behavior explicitly out of scope for security reports, so I'm filing this as a regular bug, not anything CVE-worthy.

Here's where it actually bites people:

- **There's no XML-only way to say "fail on everything except X."** This is a really common pattern when teams are migrating toward stricter test enforcement — they want to lock down most issue types but temporarily allow one category they haven't cleaned up yet. Right now that's just not expressible in `phpunit.xml` alone.
- People end up moving part of their config into CLI flags to work around it, which means the actual enforced behavior secretly depends on a flag buried in a CI job somewhere, instead of being visible in the committed `phpunit.xml`. A reviewer looking at `phpunit.xml` in a PR would have no idea the real behavior differs from what's written.
- Because the build fails when it shouldn't, teams often "fix" it by weakening things further — turning off `failOnAllIssues` entirely, or suppressing more than they meant to — which quietly lowers their overall test-quality bar as a side effect of working around this bug.
- Since this affects all 13 flags, not just self-deprecations, it hits anyone using `failOnAllIssues="true"` as a strict mode and trying to add any single documented exception through XML — deprecations, self/direct/indirect deprecations, PHPUnit's own deprecations/notices/warnings, empty suites, incomplete/risky/skipped tests, warnings, all of it.
- Teams following the natural adoption path (turn on `failOnAllIssues`, then relax specific categories as they clean things up) will hit this immediately and may wrongly conclude the whole feature is broken, rather than realizing it's just an XML/CLI parity gap.

## The relevant code

`src/TextUI/ShellExitCodeCalculator.php` (lines 60–70):
```php
$failOnSelfDeprecation     = $failOnDeprecation;
$failOnDirectDeprecation   = $failOnDeprecation;
$failOnIndirectDeprecation = $failOnDeprecation;

if ($configuration->failOnSelfDeprecation()) {
    $failOnSelfDeprecation = true;
}

if ($configuration->doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation()) {
    $failOnSelfDeprecation = false;
}
```

`src/TextUI/Configuration/Merger.php` (lines 234–238):
```php
$doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation = false;

if ($cliConfiguration->hasDoNotFailOnSelfDeprecation()) {
    $doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation = $cliConfiguration->doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation();
}
```

## What I think would fix it

I see two reasonable approaches here:

**Option A** — make `Merger.php` read `doNotFailOn*` from XML too, the same way every other `failOn*` setting already does. `failOnSelfDeprecation` a few lines above already falls back to XML correctly, so this would just be mirroring that pattern for the negative flags. It'd need corresponding `doNotFailOn*` attributes added to the schema and to `Xml/PHPUnit.php` / `Xml/Loader.php`:

```php
// Merger.php — proposed
$doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation = false;

if ($cliConfiguration->hasDoNotFailOnSelfDeprecation()) {
    $doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation = $cliConfiguration->doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation();
} elseif ($xmlConfiguration->phpunit()->hasDoNotFailOnSelfDeprecation()) {
    $doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation = $xmlConfiguration->phpunit()->doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation();
}
```
(and the same for all 13 flags)

**Option B** — a smaller patch: since `failOnSelfDeprecation()` is already correctly wired from XML with its own `false` default, `ShellExitCodeCalculator` could treat an *explicit* `failOnSelfDeprecation="false"` as authoritative over `failOnAllIssues`, if the configuration layer exposed a tri-state ("unset" vs "true" vs "false") instead of a plain boolean. `failOnEmptyTestSuite` already does something like this via `hasFailOnEmptyTestSuite()`, so there's precedent in the codebase:

```php
// following the existing hasFailOnEmptyTestSuite() precedent
if ($configuration->hasFailOnSelfDeprecation()) {
    $failOnSelfDeprecation = $configuration->failOnSelfDeprecation();
} elseif ($configuration->doNotFailOnSelfDeprecation()) {
    $failOnSelfDeprecation = false;
}
```

Option A stays more consistent with how CLI/XML parity is handled everywhere else in the codebase. Option B is a smaller diff but touches more files to add the tri-state distinction. Either way, I'd suggest applying the fix to all 13 affected flags at once rather than just `failOnSelfDeprecation`, since the same bug exists in every one of them.

## Proof of concept

Verified against `main` (`PHPUnit 13.3-g92a2b54`, PHP 8.4.22):

```console
$ php phpunit --configuration phpunit.xml
[...]
OK, but there were issues!
Tests: 1, Assertions: 1, Deprecations: 1.
$ echo $?
1        # bug: should be 0

$ php phpunit --configuration phpunit.xml --do-not-fail-on-self-deprecation
[... identical output ...]
$ echo $?
0        # only reachable via CLI, no XML equivalent exists
```

All three reproduction files are included above — `src/FirstParty.php`, `tests/SelfDeprecationTest.php`, and `phpunit.xml`. No external dependencies beyond PHPUnit itself.



