#### Summary

If a test adds a `#[Retry]` or a `#[Repeat]` attribute, the test objects that are embedded in the respective `TestSuite*` collections only get 'default' as a group, even if the `#[Group]` attribute is specified.

#### Current behavior

See above

#### How to reproduce

Add a test like
```
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace Drupal\Tests\Core\Layout;

use PHPUnit\Framework\TestCase;
use PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\Group;
use PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\Repeat;
use PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\Retry;

#[Group('Foo')]
class LayoutAttributeTest extends TestCase {

  #[Group('Bar')]
  #[Repeat(3)]
  public function testMissingProperties(): void {
    $this->assertTrue(TRUE);
  }

}
```

neither `phpunit --group Foo` nor `phpunit --group Bar` discover and execute the test. Same using #[Retry] instead of #[Repeat].

#### Expected behavior

When `#[Group]` attribute is specified, it should be accessible reading the test metadata.

Upon updating to 13.2.0 PHPStan is now telling us that setting an environment variable to an empty string is not permitted. Environment variables containing empty strings are perfectly valid. I've tracked this down to this change: 82848be7178feec5a95ca16e3f7c8375b8da09a1.

The following test works perfectly fine, but PHPStan throws an error.

```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

use PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\CoversNothing;
use PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\WithEnvironmentVariable;
use PHPUnit\Framework\TestCase;

#[CoversNothing]
final class MyTest extends TestCase
{
    #[WithEnvironmentVariable('FOO', '')]
    public function testFoo(): void
    {
        $this->assertSame('', getenv('FOO'));
        $this->assertSame('', $_ENV['FOO']);
    }
}
```

>  `Parameter #2 $value of attribute class PHPUnit\Framework\Attributes\WithEnvironmentVariable constructor expects non-empty-string|null, '' given.`

As a follow-up of the interesting discussion on #6361 regarding timeouts in milliseconds; it does seems that `$event->telemetryInfo()->duration()->asFloat();` allows returning miliseconds. Maybe defining the configuration value's format could be reconsidered?

- The main goal I'd have is to let the `Unit` suite fail when a test exceeds 50ms. 
- A stretch goal could be that defining `timeoutForSmallTests` would be definable on suite level.

The following code sample shows how milliseconds could be used (note: did not verify it yet at this phase):

```php
<?php
declare(strict_types=1);

namespace Tests\Extensions;

use PHPUnit\Event\Test\Finished;
use PHPUnit\Event\Test\FinishedSubscriber;
use PHPUnit\Runner\Extension\Extension;
use PHPUnit\Runner\Extension\Facade;
use PHPUnit\Runner\Extension\ParameterCollection;
use PHPUnit\TextUI\Configuration\Configuration;

final class TimeLimitExtension implements Extension
{
    public function bootstrap(
        Configuration $configuration,
        Facade $facade,
        ParameterCollection $parameters
    ): void {
        // Register our custom subscriber to trigger when a test finishes
        $facade->registerSubscriber(new class implements FinishedSubscriber {
            public function notify(Finished $event): void
            {
                // PHPUnit provides duration in seconds with microsecond precision
                $duration = $event->telemetryInfo()->duration()->asFloat();
                $maxAllowedSeconds = 0.050; // 50 milliseconds

                if ($duration > $maxAllowedSeconds) {
                    $testName = $event->test()->id();
                    $msSpent = round($duration * 1000, 2);

                    // Mark the test as failed due to execution time breach
                    throw new \RuntimeException(
                        "Test [{$testName}] exceeded the 50ms speed limit! Took {$msSpent}ms."
                    );
                }
            }
        });
    }
}
```

